\begin_layout Section
Introduction to Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a commutative ring with identity such that every nonzero element in
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is invertible.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Characteristic of a Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The 
\series bold
characteristic 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,F$
\end_inset

, is the smallest positive integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\cdot1_{F}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If such an integer doesn't exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{char}\,F=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Roots and Irreducibles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 A number 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{proprootdivide}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a nonconstant polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=(X-\alpha)g(X)\label{eq:root}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:root})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 is Euclidean domain and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg f(X)\geq1$
\end_inset

, there exists nonzero a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $q(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 and a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=(X-\alpha)q(X)+r\label{euclideandivroot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{euclideandivroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=(X-\alpha)q(X)$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $X-\alpha$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For most fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, there are polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 without a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (for instance consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[X]$
\end_inset

).
 If we are willing to enlarge the field, then we can discover some roots.
 This is due to Kronecker, by the following argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremrootinlargerfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 There is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Choose an irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\mid f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 too.
 Therefore it suffices to find a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Inside of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a subfield: the congruence classes represented by constants.
 There is a also a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, namely the class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{X}$
\end_inset

 for the congruence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the congruence 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)\equiv0\text{ mod }\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 becomes the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\overline{X})=0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By repeating the construction in the proof of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremrootinlargerfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 several times, we can always create a field with a full set of roots for
 our polynomial.
 We state this as a corollary, and give a proof by induction on the degree.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)=c_{m}X^{m}+\cdots+c_{0}$
\end_inset

 be in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 There is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supset K$
\end_inset

 such that in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=c_{m}(X-\alpha_{1})\cdots(X-\alpha_{m}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We induct on the degree 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The case 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 is clear, using 
\begin_inset Formula $L=K$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremrootinlargerfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $L\supset K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[X]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(X)=(X-\alpha_{1})g(X),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g(X)=m-1$
\end_inset

.
 The leading coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{m}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 has smaller degree than 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

, by induction on the degree there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $E\supset L$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 decomposes into linear factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]$
\end_inset

, so we get the desired factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\backslash
label{correlprimecommonroot}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 They are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

 if and only if they do not have a common root in any extension field of
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)u(X)+g(X)v(X)=1\label{relprime1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $u(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 If there were an 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 which is a common root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

, then substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{relprime1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 makes the left side 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 while the right side 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 have no common root in any field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

 are not relatively prime in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

 is a (nonconstant) common factor.
 There is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $h(X)$
\end_inset

 has a root, and this root will be a common root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Although adjoining one root of an irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}[X]$
\end_inset

 to the rational numbers does not always produce the other roots in the
 same field (such as with 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{3}-2$
\end_inset

), the situation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 is much simpler.
 We will see later that for an irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

, a larger field which contains one root must contain 
\emph on
all 
\emph default
the roots.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Divisibility and Roots in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{proprootdivide})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be improved as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 in some larger field, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(X)=\pi(X)g(X)\label{eq:root-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $g(X)\in K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 in both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:root-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 have a common root, so by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Corollary~(
\backslash
ref{correlprimecommonroot})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 they have a common factor in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, this means 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[X]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Finite Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 be a monic irreducible polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]$
\end_inset

 of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Then the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The cosets mod 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 are represented by remainders
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{0}+c_{1}X+\cdots+c_{n-1}X^{n-1},\qquad c_{i}\in\mathbb{F}_{p}
\]

\end_inset

and there are 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 of these.
 Since the modulus 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(X)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We will see that every finite field is isomorphic to a field of the form
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}[X]\slash\langle\pi(X)\rangle$
\end_inset

, so these polynomial constructions gives us working models over any finite
 field.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a finite field.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 is cyclic.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $q=|K|$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $|K^{\times}|=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 be the maximal order among all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show 
\begin_inset Formula $m=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 By Lagrange's Theorem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m\mid q-1$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq q-1$
\end_inset

.
 It is a theorem from group theory that every order of every element must
 divide the maximal order.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K^{\times}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore all numbers in 
\begin_inset Formula $K^{\times}$
\end_inset

 are roots of the polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{m}-1$
\end_inset

.
 The number of roots of a polynomial over a field is at most the degree
 of the polynomial, so 
\begin_inset Formula $q-1\leq m$
\end_inset

.
 Combining both inequalities gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $m=q-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field.
 The 
\series bold
characteristic 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}(F)$
\end_inset

, is the smallest positive integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\cdot1_{F}=0$
\end_inset

.
 If such an integer doesn't exist, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}(F)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{Q}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}\mathbb{F}_{p}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The characteristic of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is either 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 or a prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then we are done, so assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is not prime.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=ab$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m\cdot1_{F}=(a\cdot1_{F})(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $(a\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $(b\cdot1_{F})=0$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we get a contradiction since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F\leq a,b<m$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:\mathbb{Z}\to F$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n)=n\cdot1_{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is a ring homomorphism.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/\mbox{Ker}\varphi\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mbox{ch}F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)=0$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction, so 
\begin_inset Formula $m=p$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{p}\cong\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}\subseteq F$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ch}F=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}\cong\varphi(\mathbb{Z})\subseteq F$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 contains an isomorphic copy of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 In either case, we call this the 
\series bold
prime subfield 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Field Extension) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be fields.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
field extension 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset K$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a vector space over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
degree 
\series default
of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]$
\end_inset

, is the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{R}:\mathbb{R}]=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathbb{C}:\mathbb{R}]=2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, can we find a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=0$
\end_inset

 has a solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

? Yes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then there is a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing (an isomorphic copy of) 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with this isomorphic copy which is contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we'll regard 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 as a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

, which is a PID, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:F[x]\to F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

 be the canonical projection map given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(a(x))=\overline{a(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:=\pi_{_{\mid F}}$
\end_inset

 gives a ring homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(1)\neq0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ker}\varphi=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 Finally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\overline{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha) & =p(\overline{x})\\
 & =\overline{p(x)}\\
 & =\overline{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 be an irreducible polynomial over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K:=F[x]/\langle p(x)\rangle$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:=\bar{x}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

-basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a field, 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, so there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 with either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g(x)}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overline{g(x)} & =\overline{q(x)p(x)+r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{r(x)}\\
 & =\overline{c_{0}+c_{1}x+\cdots+c_{\ell}x^{\ell}}\\
 & =c_{0}+c_{1}\alpha+\cdots+c_{\ell}\alpha^{\ell}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)\in\mbox{Span}\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\alpha,\dots,\alpha^{n-1}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0},b_{1},\dots,b_{n-1}\in F$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}\alpha+\cdots+b_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}=\bar{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}+b_{1}x+\cdots+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}=p(x)q(x)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, so we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x)=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq n-1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Algebraic Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if there exists a nonzero polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
transcendental
\series default
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L/K$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
algebraic 
\series default
if every 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\pi)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T-\pi$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, it is a nontrivial theorem that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is transcendental over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The imaginary number 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(i)=0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in K$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then there is a unique monic irreducible polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\mid f(x)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 be a polynomial of minimal degree having 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as a root.
 We can assume, without loss of generality, that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is monic.
 We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

 is irreducible in 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose not.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=a(x)b(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $a(x),b(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}a(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq\mbox{deg}b(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=p(\alpha)=a(\alpha)b(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 implies either 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $b(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Next, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F[x]$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean Domain, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x),r(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=q(x)p(x)+r(x)$
\end_inset

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{deg}r(x)<\mbox{deg}p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(\alpha)=f(\alpha)-q(\alpha)p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts the minimality of the degree of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that if 
\begin_inset Formula $K/F$
\end_inset

 is a field extension, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 In this case, the degree of the extension 
\begin_inset Formula $[F(\alpha):F]$
\end_inset

 is the degree of the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K\subseteq L$
\end_inset

 are field extensions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:F]=[L:K][K:F]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[K:F]=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=m$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\beta_{1},\dots,\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\alpha_{1}\beta_{1},\dots,\alpha_{m}\beta_{\ell}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)=x^{3}+3x-1$
\end_inset

 is irreducible over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\pm1)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 But there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\notin\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\in\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})\subseteq\mathbb{Q}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $3=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})][\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2}):\mathbb{Q}]=[\mathbb{Q}(\alpha):\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})]\cdot2$
\end_inset

 which is a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})=\cdots=F(\alpha_{1})(\alpha_{2})\cdots(\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}\in K$
\end_inset

 are all algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=\mbox{deg}m_{\alpha_{i},F}$
\end_inset

.
 We have a sequence of field extensions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\subseteq F(\alpha_{1})\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\subseteq\cdots\subseteq F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F] & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})][F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & =[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots,\alpha_{\ell}):F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2},\dots\alpha_{\ell-1})]\cdots[F(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2}):F(\alpha_{1})][F(\alpha_{1}):F]\\
 & \leq n_{\ell}\cdots n_{2}n_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 be a field extension.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

 is finite if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $K=F(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{\ell})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Algebraically Closed Field and Algebraic Closure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any field 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, there is an algebraically closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For each nonconstant monic 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{f}$
\end_inset

 denote a variable.
 Consider the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $E=F[\dots,X_{f},\dots]$
\end_inset

 and the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{f(X_{f})\mid f\mbox{ is nonconstant monic polynomial}\}$
\end_inset

.
 We check that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal.
 Suppose not.
 Then there exists nonconstant monic polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},\dots,g_{n}\in F[\dots,X_{f},\dots]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1=g_{1}f_{1}(X_{f_{1}})+\cdots+g_{n}f_{n}(X_{f_{n}})$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{f_{i}}=\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is a proper ideal, it is contained in a maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}=E/\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is a field that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{f}$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Now continue this process with 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 replaced by 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}$
\end_inset

, etc...
 We obtain an ascending chain of fields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=K_{0}\subseteq K_{1}\subseteq K_{2}\subseteq\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K_{i}[x]$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\bigcup_{i=0}^{\infty}K_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field which contains 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed: If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x]$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K_{i}[x]$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\geq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{i+1}\subseteq K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop6}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be an algebraically closed field containing 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}=\{\alpha\in K\mid\alpha$
\end_inset

 is algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F\}$
\end_inset

 is an algebraic closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}$
\end_inset

 is a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\bar{F}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F\subset F(\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 is finite, hence algebraic.
 So all combinations 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

, etc..
 are still algebraic over 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, so they are all in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{F}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Seperable Extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be a field and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=a_{n}(x-\alpha_{1})^{n_{1}}\cdots(x-\alpha_{k})^{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 be the factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 in a splitting field, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 are distinct roots and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}\ge1$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
simple root 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn6}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\in F[x]$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
separable 
\series default
if it has only simple roots.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example5}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=x^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{F}_{2}[x]$
\end_inset

 is not separable since 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+1=(x+1)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Splitting Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

 is nonconstant, there is a field extension 
\begin_inset Formula $K'\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 picks up a root, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=(T-\alpha)g(T)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K'[T]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg g=\deg f-1$
\end_inset

.
 By applying the same process to 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)$
\end_inset

 and continuing in this way finitely many times, we reach an extension 
\begin_inset Formula $L\slash K$
\end_inset

 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors: in 
\begin_inset Formula $L[T]$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(T)=c(T-\alpha_{1})\cdots(T-\alpha_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call the field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha_{1},\dots,\alpha_{n})$
\end_inset

 that is generated by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 a 
\series bold
splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 The idea is that in a splitting field we can find a full set of rotos of
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on
no smaller field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
has that property.
 Let's look at some examples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}+1$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(i,-i)=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2})$
\end_inset

, since we pick up two roots 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 in the field generated by just one of the roots.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{2}-2$
\end_inset

 splits into linear factors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}[T]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}[T]$
\end_inset

, a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $(T-\sqrt[4]{2})(T+\sqrt[4]{2})(T-i\sqrt[4]{2})(T+i\sqrt[4]{2})$
\end_inset

.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i).
\]

\end_inset

In the second description one of the field generators is not a root of the
 original polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

.
 This is a simpler way of writing the splitting field.
 A splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}(\sqrt[4]{2},i\sqrt[4]{2})=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

These examples illustrate that, as with irreducibility, the choice of base
 field is an important part of determining the splitting field.
 Over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 has a splitting field that is an extension of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

, while over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 the splitting field of the same polynomial is an extension (of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

!) of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theoremsplittingfield}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 be a field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 be nonconstant in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 are splitting fields of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K]$
\end_inset

, there is a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 fixing all of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and the number of such isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{4}-2$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $8$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphism to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt[4]{2},i)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{2}-2)(T^{2}-3)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 has degree 
\begin_inset Formula $4$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{2},\sqrt{3})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Homomorphisms on Polynomial Coefficients
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we will use an inductive argument involving homomorphisms between polynomial
 rings.
 Any field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F\to F'$
\end_inset

 extends to a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon F[T]\to F'[T]$
\end_inset

 as follows: for 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}c_{i}T^{i}\in F[T]$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=\sum_{i=0}^{n}\sigma(c_{i})T^{i}\in F'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 We call this map 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to the coefficients.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=c_{n}T^{n}+c_{n-1}T^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}T+c_{0}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}\in F$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in F$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma(f(\alpha)) & =\sigma(c_{n}\alpha^{n}+c_{n-1}\alpha^{n-1}+\cdots+c_{1}\alpha+c_{0})\\
 & =\sigma(c_{n})\sigma(\alpha)^{n}+\sigma(c_{n-1})\sigma(\alpha)^{n-1}+\cdots+\sigma(c_{1})\sigma(\alpha)+\sigma(c_{0})\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma f)(\sigma(\alpha)) & =\sigma(f(\alpha))\\
 & =\sigma(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 sends any root of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 to a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $F'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Proof of the Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rather than prove 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 directly, we formula a more general theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism of fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 be a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=[L':K']$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 extends to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and the number of such extensions is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] & L' 
\backslash

\backslash
 K  
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash]  & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] 
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We argue by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $L'=K'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $[L':K']=1$
\end_inset

.
 The only extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, so the number of extensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $1=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]>1$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is generated as a field over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 by the roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in L$
\end_inset

 that is not in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

.
 Fix this 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for the rest of the proof.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 be the minimal polynomial of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 If there's an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\sigma\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)) & =(\widetilde{\sigma}\pi)(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(\pi(\alpha))\\
 & =\widetilde{\sigma}(0)\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first equality comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 having coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 (so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on those coefficients).
 Therefore the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 - to be determined - must come from roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 has a root in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism, applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

 (the inverse applies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K'[T]$
\end_inset

), so 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)\mid f(T)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)\mid(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible, 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 is monic irreducible (ring isomorphisms preserve irreducibility).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

 by the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

, its factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

 splits completely in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'[T]$
\end_inset

.
 Pick a root 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\in L'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $d=\deg\pi(T)=\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $d=[K(\alpha):K]>1$
\end_inset

).
 This information is in the diagram below, and there are at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 choices for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 The minimal polynomials of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 (resp.) are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(T)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,dashed] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

There is a 
\emph on
unique 
\emph default
extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\colon K\to K'$
\end_inset

 to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\mapsto\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show uniqueness.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 , then the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined everywhere on 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K[\alpha]$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'\left(\sum_{i=0}^{m}c_{i}\alpha^{i}\right) & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma'(c_{i})(\sigma'(\alpha))^{i}\\
 & =\sum_{i=0}^{m}\sigma(c_{i})\alpha'^{i}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In other words, a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 goes to the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

-polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is applied to the coefficients.
 Thus there is at most one 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)=\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 exists, we will build an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 with the desired behavior on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 It can be like this for more than one polynomial: perhaps 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)=g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(T)\in K[T]$
\end_inset

.
 In that case 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)\equiv g(T)\text{ mod }\pi(T)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)=g(T)+\pi(T)h(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients on both sides, which is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)=(\sigma g)(T)+(\sigma\pi)(T)(\sigma h)(T)$
\end_inset

, and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\alpha'$
\end_inset

 kills off the second term, leaving us with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(\alpha')=(\sigma g)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore it is 
\emph on
well-defined 
\emph default
to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)\mapsto(\sigma f)(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 This function is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

.
 Since applying 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 to coefficients is a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K[T]\to K'[T]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)\to K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy=f(\alpha)g(\alpha)=(fg)(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 (evaluation at 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative) so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma'(xy) & =\sigma(fg)(\alpha')\\
 & =((\sigma f)(\sigma g))(\alpha')\\
 & =(\sigma f)(\alpha')(\sigma g)(\alpha')\\
 & =\sigma'(x)\sigma'(y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{-1}\colon K'\to K$
\end_inset

 to go the other way shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is a field isomorphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Place 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 in the field diagram below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, dashed] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we can finally induct on degrees of splitting fields.
 Take as new base fields 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, which are isomorphic by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, it's also a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

 is a splitting field of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 and thus also over the larger field 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f(T)$
\end_inset

 has its coefficients in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'=\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma'f)(T)=(\sigma f)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 So the top square in the above diagram is like the square in the theorem
 itself, except the splitting field degrees dropped: since 
\begin_inset Formula $d>1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[L:K(\alpha)]=\frac{[L:K]}{d}<[L:K].
\]

\end_inset

By induction, 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]=[L':K'(\alpha')]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 has an extension to a field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 extends 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 itself has an extension to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
[L:K] & =[L:K(\alpha)]d\\
 & =[L':K'(\alpha')]d\\
 & =[L':K'].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

(If the proof started with 
\begin_inset Formula $K'=K$
\end_inset

, it would usually be false that 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Theorem~(
\backslash
ref{theoremsplittingfield})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is not directly accessible to our inductive proof.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 has at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K]$
\end_inset

 extensions to an isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 First we show every isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}\colon L\to L'$
\end_inset

 extending 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the extension of some intermediate isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 with a subfield of 
\begin_inset Formula $L'$
\end_inset

.
 From the start of the proof, 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 must be a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha':=\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K}=\sigma$
\end_inset

, the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is a field homomorphism that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and sends 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $K(\alpha)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K'(\widetilde{\sigma}(\alpha))=K'(\alpha')$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a lift of the intermediate field isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma':=\widetilde{\sigma}|_{K(\alpha)}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd} L 
\backslash
arrow[r, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\backslash
widetilde{
\backslash
sigma }
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] & L' 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K(
\backslash
alpha ) 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma '
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash] & K' (
\backslash
alpha ') 
\backslash
arrow[u, dash] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\backslash

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

K 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

] 
\backslash
arrow[r,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\backslash
sigma 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

] & K' 
\backslash
arrow[u,dash,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

d
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,swap]  
\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

By induction on degrees of splitting fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 lifts to at most 
\begin_inset Formula $[L:K(\alpha)]$
\end_inset

 isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'(\alpha)$
\end_inset

, which is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma\pi)(T)$
\end_inset

, the number of maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $\deg(\sigma\pi)(T)=d$
\end_inset

.
 The number of isomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

 that lift 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the number of homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'\colon K(\alpha)\to L'$
\end_inset

 lifting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 times the number of extensions of each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma'$
\end_inset

 to an isomoprhism 
\begin_inset Formula $L\to L'$
\end_inset

, and that total is at most 
\begin_inset Formula $d[L:K(\alpha)]=[L:K]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

